ğŸ”¹ 1. DFA: Deterministic Finite Automata
What is a DFA?

A DFA is a 5-tuple:
M = (Q, Î£, Î´, qâ‚€, F)

Part	Meaning
Q	Finite set of states
Î£ (sigma)	Input alphabet
Î´	Transition function: Î´(q, a) â†’ q'
qâ‚€	Start state (qâ‚€ âˆˆ Q)
F	Set of final (accepting) states
Key Properties:

Deterministic: At each step, only ONE possible next state.

No ambiguity.

Every input symbol must have a defined transition in every state.




ğŸ”¹ 2. NFA: Nondeterministic Finite Automata
Whatâ€™s different?

Still a 5-tuple: (Q, Î£, Î´, qâ‚€, F)

BUT:

Î´(q, a) can return multiple states

Transitions can be missing

More than one possible path for input

ğŸ‘‰ A string is accepted if at least one path leads to a final state.

Why do we care?

NFAs are easier to design

Every NFA can be converted to a DFA




ğŸ”¹ 3. Îµ-NFA: NFA with Epsilon (Îµ) Transitions

Adds a new twist:

Îµ-transitions: move from one state to another without consuming input

So, the machine can "move silently" to another state

To simulate:

Before reading input symbol, check Îµ-closure:

Set of all states reachable using only Îµ-transitions.



ğŸ”¹ 4. Conversions
NFA â†’ DFA

Use subset construction

DFA states = sets of NFA states

Can be exponential in size


Îµ-NFA â†’ DFA

First: convert Îµ-NFA to NFA by computing Îµ-closures

Then: convert that NFA to DFA




ğŸ”¹ 5. Moore vs Mealy Machines (Machines with Output)

Both are Finite State Machines with outputs â€” but:

Feature             |     	Moore Machine            |        	Mealy Machine
Output depends on	  |           State                |    	State and input symbol
Output appears	    |   On entering a state          |     	On transitions
Notation            | 	Output is shown on state     |	Output is shown on edge (input/output)





